Checking data where Language Detection scores are low

  • 'German' - Original data from German files
  • 'English' - Original data from English files
  • 'Lang_Detection_German - Score using custom function to detect (language and probability for that language)
    • e.g. ("de",".4") - means the language detected is "de" i.e. German and probability score that it is German is .4
  • 'Lang_Detection_English' - Score using custom function to detect (language and probability for that language)
    • e.g. ("en",".4") - means the language detected is "de" i.e. German and probability score that it is German is .4
  • 'Not_Selected_Reason' - computed based on following criteria
    • If language in German column is something other than German it returns a reason that "Language is not German"
    • If probability score for the language in German column is less than a threshold it returns a reason "-Detection score for German is less than threshold-"
    • Same is for English column
    • Threshold can be chosen based on how much data is to be weeded out, what confidence score we want to go with.

In [12]:
def selection_criteria(de,en,detect_threshold=.8):
    reason_=""
    try:
        if(de[0]!="de"): 
            reason_="-Language is not detected as German-"
        if(de[1]<detect_threshold): 
           reason_= reason_+"-Detection score for German is less than threshold-"
        if(en[0]!="en"):
            reason_=reason_+"-Language is not detected as English-"
        if(en[1]<detect_threshold):
            reason_=reason_+"-Detection score for English is less than threshold-"
    except Exception as e:
        print(e)
    finally:   
        return reason_

Translation Score¶

  • 'Translation_de_en' - Translation using google translate for German sentences to English

  • 'Translation_en_de' - Translation using google translate for English sentences to German

  • 'Translation_Score_de_en'- Quality of translation from German to English

  • 'Translation_Score_en_de'- Quality of translation from English to German

  • 'Translation_Avg_Score' - Average score of "German to English" and "English to German translation"

  • similarity_score() function

    • Custom function used to calculate translation score
    • It uses GoogleTranslator as well as transformer library with cosine similarity to determine this score
    • The definition is given in functions_used.ipynb

Function to calculate LT Scores¶

  • LT stands for Language and Translation Score
  • It takes in dataframe with German and English columns and returns as input two dataframe
    • Selected data after calculating all the Language and Translation related scores
      • The selected data meets the threshold scores
      • The rejected data is moved to rejected dataframe
    • Rejected data where the threshold value is not met
      • Rejected data as appropriate rejection reason
  • Dependencies - these are to be met for this function to work
    • Using following functions
      • language_detection_score() - detects language with the probaility score for a text
      • selection_criteria() - returns a reason for rejecting a record based on the threshold values
      • cosine_similarity() - determines the similarity between two text of same language
    • Following libraries are needed for it's proper functioning
      • pipeline - transformer library used for translation
      • CountVectorizer - for vectorization
      • sys, traceback - for exception handling
      • pandas - general dataframe related functionality
      • math, string - general application
In [29]:
def calculate_LT_scores(data_LT,d_threshold,t_threshold):
    from transformers import pipeline
    data_dropped=pd.DataFrame(columns=["key","German","English","Not_Selected_Reason","Reason_Code"])
    try:
        data_LT["Lang_Detection_German"]=data_LT["German"].apply(lambda x:language_detection_score(x))
        data_LT["Lang_Detection_English"]=data_LT["English"].apply(lambda x:language_detection_score(x))

        translator_de_en = pipeline("translation", model="Helsinki-NLP/opus-mt-de-en")
        translator_en_de = pipeline("translation", model="Helsinki-NLP/opus-mt-en-de")

        data_LT["Translation_de_en"]=data_LT.apply(lambda x: translator_de_en(x.German)[0].get("translation_text"), axis=1)
        data_LT["Translation_en_de"]=data_LT.apply(lambda x: translator_en_de(x.English)[0].get("translation_text"), axis=1)
        data_LT["Translation_Score_de_en"]=data_LT.apply(lambda x: cosine_similarity(x.Translation_de_en,x.English), axis=1)
        data_LT["Translation_Score_en_de"]=data_LT.apply(lambda x: cosine_similarity(x.Translation_en_de,x.German), axis=1)
        data_LT["Translation_Avg_Score"]=data_LT.apply(lambda x:np.mean([x.Translation_Score_de_en,x.Translation_Score_en_de]), axis=1)

        data_LT["Not_Selected_Reason"]=data_LT.apply(lambda x: selection_criteria(x["Lang_Detection_German"],x["Lang_Detection_English"],d_threshold),axis=1)
        data_temp=data_LT.query("Not_Selected_Reason!=''") # Rejected data
        data_temp["Reason_Code"]="LI" # Setting reason code for rejecting/dropping data
        data_dropped=pd.concat([data_dropped,data_temp],ignore_index=True) # Storing rejected data
        data_LT=data_LT.query("Not_Selected_Reason==''") # Selected data
        data_LT.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True) # reindexing # redundant step in a function
        data_LT.drop(["Not_Selected_Reason"], axis=1, inplace=True) # redundant

        data_temp=data_LT[data_LT.apply(lambda x : x["Translation_Avg_Score"] < translate_threshold, axis=1)] # Rejected data
        data_temp["Not_Selected_Reason"]="Average translation score is less than threshold value of "+str(t_threshold)
        data_temp["Reason_Code"]="TI" # Setting reason code for rejecting/dropping data
        data_dropped=pd.concat([data_dropped,data_temp],ignore_index=True) # Storing rejected data
        data_LT=data_LT[data_LT.apply(lambda x : x["Translation_Avg_Score"] > translate_threshold, axis=1)] # Selected data
        data_LT.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True) # reindexing redundant step in a function
    except Exception as e:
        _,_,etrace=sys.exc_info()
        print(e,"line:"+str(etrace.tb_lineno))
    finally:   
        return data_LT, data_dropped

Counting words in each sentence for both German and English Sentences¶

  • There are multiple ways in which words can be counted in the sentence.
  • Some of them used here are
    • Regular expression
    • Spacy library
    • NLTK library
  • Other than this there are more libraries which can create tokens(words/characters)
  • Some other libraries are TEXTBLOX, Shlex, KERAS, GENSIM
  • We can also use simple split() function to achieve this
In [50]:
%%time

import nltk
try:
    data["word_count_German"]=data["German"].apply(lambda x : len(nltk.tokenize.WhitespaceTokenizer().tokenize(x))) # NLTK library
    data["word_count_English"]=data["English"].apply(lambda x : len(nltk.tokenize.WhitespaceTokenizer().tokenize(x))) # NLTK library
    # data["word_count_German"]=data["word_count_German"].astype(int) 
    # data["word_count_English"]=data["word_count_English"].astype(int) .astype(int)    
    data["character_count_German"]=data["German"].apply(lambda x: len(x))    
    data["character_count_English"]=data["English"].apply(lambda x: len(x))    
except Exception as e:
    print(e)

%%time
import jenkspy
for wc_lan in ["word_count_German","word_count_English"]:
    cnt_lst=data[wc_lan].to_list()
    cnt_lst.sort()
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(1,4,figsize=(16,2),sharey=True, constrained_layout=True); # Creating 4 subplots
    for i in [2,3,4,5]:
        bins=i
        breaks = jenkspy.jenks_breaks(cnt_lst, n_classes=bins)
        # labels
        labels=[]
        ticks=[]
        for j in range(i):
            labels.append(str(breaks[j])+'-'+str(breaks[j+1]))
        data['bin_cut_break'] = pd.cut(cnt_lst , bins=breaks, labels=labels, include_lowest=True)
        ax=axes[i-2]
        _=ax.hist(data['bin_cut_break'],bins=bins,edgecolor="black")
        for p in ax.patches:
            x1 = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2 
            y1 = p.get_y() + p.get_height() + .02*len(cnt_lst) # adjustment for label on top of bars
            _=ax.annotate(round(p.get_height()), (x1, y1), size = 10,ha="center")
            ticks.append(x1)
        _=ax.set_ylim([0, len(cnt_lst)]) # Number of records
        # _=ax.set_yticks(np.arange(0,21001,5000))    
        _=ax.set_xticks(ticks)
        _=ax.set_yticks([])
        _=ax.set_xticklabels(labels, fontsize=9)
        _=ax.set_title(str(bins)+' bins');
        _=ax.set_xlabel('Plot'+str(i-1),fontsize=10,fontweight='bold')
        _=plt.suptitle("Jenkspy bins on "+wc_lan,color="green",fontweight="bold")

Data Selection¶

  • We will start with small dataset with sentences having 10 or less words
  • Create a simple RNN/ LSTM and check how it performs
  • Based on the performance will check and proceed further
  • Creating a dynamic filer so that it can be used later to pull out relevant data
    • If we want data for words less than 10 wcnt value can be changed
    • If we want to pull data for English sentences the value for parameter lan_ will can be dynamically changed to "English"
In [13]:
def get_data(data,lan_,wcnt_,operator_='<='):
    '''takes in input language, word counts and operator
    returns the data based on the filter    
    e.g lan_="German", operator=3, wcnt_=3 will create a filter
    "word_cnt_German==3" which will return data with word count 3 of German sentences
    '''
    filter_="word_count_"+lan_+operator_+str(wcnt_)
    data=data.query(filter_)
    return data

Custom cleaning of data¶

  • Context
    • Observed that some English sentences are way too big compared to the corresponding German sentence
    • Example - key(EP4534) : herr prasident! - "mr president, the treaty of amsterdam has set an important objective for the union"
  • There are many more such sentences which are apparantly incorrect.
  • There are two ways
    • Either we drop this data
    • Or manage this during the modeling by keeping maxlen within a range of German sentence maxlen.
  • If a German sentence is say 5 words long - corresponging English sentence will be a few less of few more words long.
  • We will apply translation_score() method to weed off this data.
In [45]:
print("="*100)
for lan_ in ["German", "English"]:
    for w_len_ in [3]:
        pkl_name_=lan_+"_"+str(w_len_)+"_word"
        # w_len_,lan_,pkl_name_
        
        data_=read_frm_pickle(pkl_name_+".pkl")
        print("\033[1mRows in data for file name {} : {:,.0f}\033[0m".format(pkl_name_+'.pkl',data_.shape[0]))
        
        # Pre-process data
        data_,_=pre_process_text(data_)
        write_to_pickle(data_,"pickle_data/"+pkl_name_+'_clean.pkl')
        print("\033[1mRows in data for file name {} : {:,.0f}\033[0m".format(pkl_name_+'_clean.pkl',data_.shape[0]))
        
        # Deleting some records to make the models train faster
        if(lan_=="German"):
             data_temp=data_.query("word_count_English>"+str(w_len_+2))
        elif(lan_=="English"):
             data_temp=data_.query("word_count_German>"+str(w_len_+2))
                
        data_=data_[~data_['key'].isin(data_temp["key"].tolist())]   
        data_.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True) # reindexing very important step
        
        write_to_pickle(data_,"pickle_data/"+pkl_name_+'_clean.pkl')    
        
        print("\033[1mRows in data for file name {} : {:,.0f}\033[0m".format(pkl_name_+'_clean.pkl',data_.shape[0]))
        print("="*100)
